 For Jameson, postmodern texts are ahistorical, playing with pastiched images and aesthetic forms, and are therefore unable to provide a critical purchase on culture and capital. For Hutcheon, postmodern fiction and architecture remain political, opening spaces for social critique through a parody that deconstructs official history. Thinking in the space between these two sharply different positions, the essays in this collection investigate a broad range of contemporary fiction, film, and architecture—from such narratives as Don DeLillo's Libra, Toni Morrison's Beloved, and Ridley Scott's Blade Runner, to the vastly different spaces of Las Vegas casinos and the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum—in order to ask what the cultural work of a postmodern aesthetic might be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aBudra, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarmichael, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Kimberly Chabot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvall, John N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuvall, John N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHogue, W. Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutcheon, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNamara, Kevin R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlster, Stacey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Nancy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaldrep, Shelton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZ